{"key":"post-10716918","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10716918</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The tek I was reading never mentioned this.&amp;nbsp; It just used a casing. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Coir is a bulk substrate material, just like manure or compost.&amp;nbsp; The reason you're confused is because whomever wrote the tek was misusing terms.&amp;nbsp; There's so many people using the wrong nomenclature around here, it confuses the new people, and then they have to un-learn all the bad info.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;60/40 verm/coir was used as a 'casing' layer a quite a bit a few years ago, but in reality it was adding a top layer of bulk substrate, since mycelium derives food value from both the coir and the verm.&amp;nbsp; Cubensis fruits just fine on an uncased bulk substrate.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Skip the calcium carbonate.&amp;nbsp; You don't need a pH adjustment with bulk substrates.&amp;nbsp; Use gypsum at about 5% or so by volume to the amount of coir.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You can either mix the spawn and bulk materials together, or layer them.&amp;nbsp; I prefer to layer, but it's commonly done both ways.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10716931</next>\n<prev>10716787</prev>\n<first>10716691</first>\n<last>10717143</last>\n<when>1248223171</when>\n<utime>07/22/09 03:39 AM</utime>\n</post>"}